The commission shall:
Appoint local emergency planning committees and revise these committees as it deems appropriate. The committees shall include, as a minimum, representatives from each of the following groups:
Elected local officials;
Law enforcement;
Emergency management;
Fire service;
First aid;
Health service;
Local environmental;
Hospital;
Transportation;
Broadcast and print media;
Community groups; and
Owners and operators of facilities subject to this chapter;
Adopt standards and procedures for the operations of local committees;
Develop reporting requirements and procedures consistent with those of Title III, Pub. L. No. 99-499, for individuals, businesses, and governmental agencies that manufacture, use, store, or transport hazardous substances;
Develop guidance and standards for plans related to hazardous substances;
Approve, disapprove, and, where necessary, make recommendations to improve plans developed by local emergency planning committees;
Recommend administrative regulations to the director for issuance by the Division of Emergency Management to implement provisions of this chapter, consistent with Title III, Pub. L. No. 99-499;
Receive from any source and authorize the expenditure of funds;
Develop policies relating to the training of committees and persons subject to respond to releases of hazardous substances;
Develop policies relating to exercising and testing plans developed by local emergency planning committees;
Specify a warning point to which all required emergency notifications shall be made;
Develop a procedure by which facilities may report the presence and inventories of hazardous substances and by which members of the public may obtain these reports;
Annually review all commission policies and procedures and update them as necessary; and
Adopt policies for the conduct of the business and duties of the commission.
